17.145 | Political Economy of Technology and Development in Latin America | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=17.145 Political Economy of Technology and Development in Latin America | prereq:none instructors:B. Schneider term:Acad Year 2016-2017: U (Spring) Acad Year 2017-2018: Not offered description:Presents a broad, historical overview of the political economy of development in Latin America, especially Mexico, Brazil, and Chile. Examines the ways in which these countries rely heavily on foreign technology transfer, especially through multinational corporations, but experience low levels of investment in R&D and education. Addresses some of the pivotal theoretical and policy disputes over the appropriate mix of state and market, the optimum balance between foreign and domestic sources of capital and technology, and the trade-off between growth and equity.  3-0-9 units. HASS-S; CI-H
17.150 | The American Political Economy in Comparative Perspective | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=17.150 The American Political Economy in Comparative Perspective | prereq:permission of instructor instructors:K. Thelen term:Acad Year 2016-2017: Not offered Acad Year 2017-2018: G (Fall) description:Examines the origins and impact of key features of the American political economy in comparative perspective. Considers a range of political-economic topics, including labor markets, finance, taxation, social policy, and the role of money and organized interests. Highlights the distinctive aspects of American political economy in terms of both institutional structure and substantive outcomes (such as poverty and inequality) by comparing the US with other nations, particularly other rich democracies.  3-0-9 units
17.154 | Varieties of Capitalism and Social Inequality | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=17.154 Varieties of Capitalism and Social Inequality | prereq:permission of instructor instructors:K. Thelen, P. Hall term:Acad Year 2016-2017: Not offered Acad Year 2017-2018: G (Fall) textbook:The Three Worlds of Welfare Capitalism (Esping-Andersen, Gosta)  description:Focuses on the advanced democracies of Europe, the United States, and Japan. Explores trajectories of change that bear on issues of economic and social inequality. Examines whether contemporary trends (globalization, deindustrialization) undermine institutional arrangements that once reconciled economic efficiency with high levels of social equality. Considers the extent to which existing theoretical frameworks capture cross-national variation in the dynamics of redistribution in these societies.  3-0-9 units
